ëóŸbarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/flow_control/if-else.mdŸ@b126618b68c531971385b692977e22000e59f7905d00bc59d441d527b7afe458ßif/elseëßif/else⁄ÎThe 
``if``
 expression evaluates a condition and then chooses to run a block based on the condition.
For example, you can print "yes", based on a true condition:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
if true {
  print yes
} else {
  print no
}

```
Alternately, you can print "no", based on a false condition:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
if false {
  print yes
} else {
  print no
}

```
The 
``else``
 part of 
``if``
 is optional. If not provided, if a condition is false, the 
``if``
 expression returns 
``null``
.
The code that follows the 
``else``
 is an expression rather than a block, allowing any number of follow-on 
``if``
 expressions as well as other types of expressions. For example, this expression returns 100: 
``if false { 1 } else 100``
.
íêê⁄Title: if/else
Path: if/else
Content:
The 
``if``
 expression evaluates a condition and then chooses to run a block based on the condition.
For example, you can print "yes", based on a true condition:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
if true {
  print yes
} else {
  print no
}

```
Alternately, you can print "no", based on a false condition:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
if false {
  print yes
} else {
  print no
}

```
The 
``else``
 part of 
``if``
 is optional. If not provided, if a condition is false, the 
``if``
 expression returns 
``null``
.
The code that follows the 
``else``
 is an expression rather than a block, allowing any number of follow-on 
``if``
 expressions as well as other types of expressions. For example, this expression returns 100: 
``if false { 1 } else 100``
.
